One America, Two Peoples
New York — As I write this, officials across the United States are still counting ballots from the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the results are finally confirmed, recounts and legal challenges will surely follow.
This was to be expected in a closely contested election with record-breaking voter turnout.
Only American citizens can vote for the president, but the choice affects people everywhere.
Now that determining the election results may still take time, it's not too early to explore the implications of this election for the world's most powerful nation.
从积极的方面看，美国仍然是一个强大的民主国家。
尽管受到与疫情大流行有关的实际限制，但选民的参与率仍然很高。
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
而且暴力事件很少发生。
Courts are investigating what appear to be politically motivated decisions by the U.S. Postal Service to impede the delivery of ballots from areas where votes are expected to be heavily Democratic.
On Tuesday evening, incumbent U.S. President Donald Trump declared victory without any evident response, while his demand to stop the count (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to fall on deaf ears.
However, it is worrying that there remains a large divide among American voters.
The two candidates’ vote counts are virtually equal.
It is unsurprising that such a division would likely lead to a divided government.
If this trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and retain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will continue to control the Senate.
Governorships and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with Republicans having a slight edge).
The anticipated "blue wave" for the Democrats did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, securing several million more than four million votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But Republicans held onto many Senate seats that were predicted to flip, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result does not come from strong authorization and is not due to political realignment.
Trump's polling situation is excellent, receiving over five million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in U.S. history and surpassing all previous winners.
Especially noteworthy is that this occurred during a period when daily new coronavirus cases and deaths reached record highs.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic became most severe, nearly half of voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems very likely, he will still have significant influence, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems very likely).
Even if he himself does not run, Trump is likely to have a considerable influence on the Republican nominee selection for the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the parties of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumponomics — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
No surprise that despite lacking any evidence, Trump is trying to portray himself as high-minded and righteous, attempting to delegitimize the election results and alleging fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden’s legitimacy as president.
Trump is likely never to concede, and certainly not to attend the inauguration of his successor.
To paraphrase Will Rogers, Trump has yet to encounter a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are living in increasingly separate worlds.
They segment themselves into communities and regions with similar views.
And every world tends to watch its own cable channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the absence of a national civics course facilitates the differentiation among different age groups.
It is worth emphasizing that the country's differentiation is not primarily along economic lines.
People from various socioeconomic backgrounds voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by race, gender, and population did not overwhelmingly favor one side as many had predicted.
Their main disagreement lies in the remedies.
Educational level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geography. Republican voters tend to live in exurbs and rural areas, while Democrats prefer urban areas.
However, culture may play a larger role in U.S. politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seemed to be of little importance in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Given this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms in how presidential elections are held or how the government operates.
This is no different from reforming the UN Security Council.
Many believe that the current system is deeply flawed and lacks representation, but consensus on reform cannot be reached because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
It is unsurprising that those who stand to lose from the change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This will largely depend on Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell and his ability and willingness to work with the Biden administration in the future.
For cooperation to take place, Biden will need to make compromises, which will undoubtedly be resisted by more ideologically rigid members of his own party.
Democrats had tried to reject Trump and everything he stood for in sharp terms.
但他们没有成功。
而共和党人寻求的是一场让特朗普得到认可的选举。
而这也没能如他们所愿。
相反，选举所揭示的是一个国家和两类国民。
他们将不得不共存；但他们是否能共存，仍有待观察。
